<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<tt xml:lang="en-US"
  xmlns="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml"
  xmlns:ttm="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#metadata"
  xmlns:tts="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#styling">
  <head>
    <metadata xmlns:ttm="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#metadata">
      <ttm:title>440570872 - 1_pgsc2tgy - PID 1530551</ttm:title>
    </metadata>
    <styling>
      <style xml:id="basic" tts:textAlign="center" />
    </styling>
  </head>

  <body>
    <div style="basic">
        <p begin="00:00:00.800" end="00:00:09.140" tts:direction="ltr">All right. This is a example of a stellar
<br />explanatory story.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:09.140" end="00:00:13.600" tts:direction="ltr">Let's dive into the example where I</p>
        <p begin="00:00:13.600" end="00:00:18.060" tts:direction="ltr">first want to remind you whenever you're
<br />showing, not telling,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:18.060" end="00:00:19.800" tts:direction="ltr">but showing a stellar story,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:19.800" end="00:00:21.560" tts:direction="ltr">you want to be sure to weave</p>
        <p begin="00:00:21.560" end="00:00:25.260" tts:direction="ltr">multiple charts together and you're going
<br />to drive your,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:25.260" end="00:00:29.100" tts:direction="ltr">your audience, to do something specific,
<br />and that's set action.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:29.100" end="00:00:33.705" tts:direction="ltr">Remember those two key things that you're
<br />accomplishing.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:33.705" end="00:00:39.090" tts:direction="ltr">Again, this is an example gathered from
<br />storytelling with data.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:39.090" end="00:00:43.290" tts:direction="ltr">This is a people update regarding sales
<br />managers,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:43.290" end="00:00:47.370" tts:direction="ltr">and the title is to rethink how we hire.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:47.370" end="00:00:50.010" tts:direction="ltr">Let me begin the example.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:50.010" end="00:00:54.190" tts:direction="ltr">Hello, I'm Lean, and I'm here for a sales
<br />Manager update,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:54.190" end="00:00:57.090" tts:direction="ltr">and I'm here to help us rethink</p>
        <p begin="00:00:57.090" end="00:01:01.260" tts:direction="ltr">how we hire sales managers in the
<br />organization.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:01.260" end="00:01:04.130" tts:direction="ltr">Let's first start with a big picture.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:04.130" end="00:01:07.430" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to look at sales manager
<br />population</p>
        <p begin="00:01:07.430" end="00:01:11.470" tts:direction="ltr">and the aspects that contribute to the
<br />head count over time.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:11.470" end="00:01:14.210" tts:direction="ltr">We're looking at the last calendar year</p>
        <p begin="00:01:14.210" end="00:01:17.290" tts:direction="ltr">aggregating from January through December.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:17.290" end="00:01:21.510" tts:direction="ltr">I want to direct your attention to the
<br />bottom of the slide on the x axis,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:21.510" end="00:01:24.550" tts:direction="ltr">where we'll start at the beginning of the
<br />head count,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:24.550" end="00:01:27.690" tts:direction="ltr">adding in hires, promos, transfers in,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:27.690" end="00:01:30.350" tts:direction="ltr">then we'll move on to transfers out,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:30.350" end="00:01:33.530" tts:direction="ltr">exits, and then the total headcount.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:33.530" end="00:01:36.090" tts:direction="ltr">This is like a visual math problem,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:36.090" end="00:01:41.350" tts:direction="ltr">where eventually it will yield end of year
<br />headcount.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:41.410" end="00:01:44.870" tts:direction="ltr">Let's start with the beginning.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:44.870" end="00:01:46.790" tts:direction="ltr">Here at the beginning,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:46.790" end="00:01:50.870" tts:direction="ltr">we started with 317 sales managers.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:50.870" end="00:01:55.130" tts:direction="ltr">Next, we added the additions of the hires.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:55.130" end="00:01:57.670" tts:direction="ltr">This is by far the largest additions,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:57.670" end="00:02:02.720" tts:direction="ltr">which accounted for about two thirds of
<br />the growth of this population.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:02.720" end="00:02:06.310" tts:direction="ltr">We also had promotions and transfers.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:06.310" end="00:02:09.250" tts:direction="ltr">You can see that 47 and 49 for</p>
        <p begin="00:02:09.250" end="00:02:13.430" tts:direction="ltr">the remaining third increase to the sales
<br />manager population.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:13.430" end="00:02:16.650" tts:direction="ltr">Now let's look at the other side of the
<br />equation,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:16.650" end="00:02:19.850" tts:direction="ltr">the deductions, and transfers out.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:19.850" end="00:02:26.350" tts:direction="ltr">We had more transfers out than we had
<br />promotions and transfers in combined,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:26.350" end="00:02:31.630" tts:direction="ltr">and we also had a great deal of exits over
<br />the course of the past year.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:31.630" end="00:02:36.860" tts:direction="ltr">You'll note that we had more exits than we
<br />had hires.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:36.860" end="00:02:39.330" tts:direction="ltr">Looking at this altogether,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:39.330" end="00:02:41.770" tts:direction="ltr">we are slightly down on the head count,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:41.770" end="00:02:43.390" tts:direction="ltr">then where will we begin.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:43.390" end="00:02:48.290" tts:direction="ltr">We also know that the overall sales
<br />organization has grown.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:48.290" end="00:02:52.430" tts:direction="ltr">You might think that we need and should
<br />hire more.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:52.430" end="00:02:56.570" tts:direction="ltr">But I'm going to suggest a different
<br />approach.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:57.930" end="00:03:01.790" tts:direction="ltr">First, I want to share with you</p>
        <p begin="00:03:01.790" end="00:03:03.890" tts:direction="ltr">some additional detail on how</p>
        <p begin="00:03:03.890" end="00:03:07.670" tts:direction="ltr">these metrics play out over the course of
<br />the year.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:07.670" end="00:03:12.050" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to focus first on these
<br />additions here.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:12.050" end="00:03:14.930" tts:direction="ltr">Let's take a look at this chart.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:14.930" end="00:03:17.870" tts:direction="ltr">Here on the y axis,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:17.870" end="00:03:19.770" tts:direction="ltr">we have the number of managers,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:19.770" end="00:03:21.670" tts:direction="ltr">and then on the x,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:21.670" end="00:03:25.470" tts:direction="ltr">we have our months going from January to
<br />December.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:25.470" end="00:03:29.770" tts:direction="ltr">And we're still looking at those managers,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:29.770" end="00:03:36.050" tts:direction="ltr">but we see that 67% of the additions were
<br />external hires.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:36.050" end="00:03:39.410" tts:direction="ltr">Every two out of three new managers came
<br />into</p>
        <p begin="00:03:39.410" end="00:03:43.050" tts:direction="ltr">the organization from outside this past
<br />year.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:43.050" end="00:03:46.530" tts:direction="ltr">So I want to highlight the fact that we
<br />have the greatest number of</p>
        <p begin="00:03:46.530" end="00:03:51.110" tts:direction="ltr">hires starting the very first of the month
<br />of each quarter.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:51.110" end="00:03:55.930" tts:direction="ltr">That's largely due to how we set our
<br />targets and sales incentives.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:55.930" end="00:04:00.970" tts:direction="ltr">However, you'll see here there are
<br />relatively few hires in the last quarter,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:00.970" end="00:04:07.175" tts:direction="ltr">that's October due to our annual promotion
<br />cycle that takes place then.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:07.175" end="00:04:10.220" tts:direction="ltr">Let's add on some additional data.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:10.220" end="00:04:11.880" tts:direction="ltr">This is the promotions,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:11.880" end="00:04:17.300" tts:direction="ltr">where we had 47 promoted over the course
<br />of the last year to Sales Manager.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:17.300" end="00:04:22.420" tts:direction="ltr">38 of those happened during our single
<br />annual promotion cycle.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:22.420" end="00:04:24.220" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to promotions,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:24.220" end="00:04:28.060" tts:direction="ltr">we already know that folks getting
<br />promoted to Sales Manager</p>
        <p begin="00:04:28.060" end="00:04:30.360" tts:direction="ltr">are a great culture fit within</p>
        <p begin="00:04:30.360" end="00:04:33.215" tts:direction="ltr">the organization and with the sales
<br />organization.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:33.215" end="00:04:36.870" tts:direction="ltr">Even more important, those promoted within
<br />tend to stay in</p>
        <p begin="00:04:36.870" end="00:04:40.930" tts:direction="ltr">the role at the organization longer than
<br />external hires.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:40.930" end="00:04:46.630" tts:direction="ltr">On the flip side and the challenges with
<br />are the single annual cycle.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:46.630" end="00:04:52.270" tts:direction="ltr">We hear complaints from leadership that it
<br />is an all consuming period of time,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:52.270" end="00:04:55.310" tts:direction="ltr">and that also anyone who is just shy of
<br />being</p>
        <p begin="00:04:55.310" end="00:04:58.230" tts:direction="ltr">promoted during this period has to wait</p>
        <p begin="00:04:58.230" end="00:05:00.870" tts:direction="ltr">an entire year before they become</p>
        <p begin="00:05:00.870" end="00:05:05.090" tts:direction="ltr">eligible again and we may lose those
<br />individuals.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:05.160" end="00:05:08.600" tts:direction="ltr">Before we move to transfers out and exits,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:08.600" end="00:05:10.500" tts:direction="ltr">I want to show you one last metric,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:10.500" end="00:05:13.700" tts:direction="ltr">and that is the incoming transfers.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:13.700" end="00:05:18.080" tts:direction="ltr">We had 49 internal transfers to sales
<br />managers,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:18.080" end="00:05:22.680" tts:direction="ltr">and this is this gray line right here,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:22.680" end="00:05:29.820" tts:direction="ltr">and you can see that those have similar
<br />trends as our hires,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:29.820" end="00:05:33.900" tts:direction="ltr">where we have those bumps at the beginning
<br />of each quarter.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:33.900" end="00:05:37.860" tts:direction="ltr">You might be able to anticipate where I'm
<br />going with this.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:37.860" end="00:05:41.745" tts:direction="ltr">If we take the energy that we're using in
<br />hiring,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:41.745" end="00:05:47.550" tts:direction="ltr">and refocus it on promotions and
<br />transfers,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:47.550" end="00:05:50.370" tts:direction="ltr">it could be a win across several fronts.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:50.370" end="00:05:51.970" tts:direction="ltr">But before we do that,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:51.970" end="00:05:55.530" tts:direction="ltr">I want to look at those deductions.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:55.580" end="00:06:00.620" tts:direction="ltr">This is the area that we'll focus on in
<br />this space right here,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:00.620" end="00:06:06.440" tts:direction="ltr">and those came from transfers out and
<br />exits.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:06.440" end="00:06:13.540" tts:direction="ltr">We had 111 sales manager transfer transfer
<br />out of the organization.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:13.540" end="00:06:17.120" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to layer on our exits with</p>
        <p begin="00:06:17.120" end="00:06:21.580" tts:direction="ltr">200 exits because they do follow a similar
<br />trend.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:21.580" end="00:06:24.280" tts:direction="ltr">January is when many of the hires from</p>
        <p begin="00:06:24.280" end="00:06:27.860" tts:direction="ltr">the prior year become eligible to
<br />transfer,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:27.860" end="00:06:30.150" tts:direction="ltr">and we can see that many of them do.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:30.150" end="00:06:33.420" tts:direction="ltr">Exits in January and February 1</p>
        <p begin="00:06:33.420" end="00:06:39.000" tts:direction="ltr">pursued an internal transfer and most
<br />likely were unsuccessful,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:39.000" end="00:06:41.660" tts:direction="ltr">and so many of those were new hires.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:41.660" end="00:06:47.480" tts:direction="ltr">We also see a spike of both those
<br />transfers and exits in November.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:47.480" end="00:06:49.920" tts:direction="ltr">These are people who thought they were
<br />ready for</p>
        <p begin="00:06:49.920" end="00:06:53.260" tts:direction="ltr">a promotion but who did not get the
<br />promotion,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:53.260" end="00:06:56.320" tts:direction="ltr">and so we see them exiting here.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:56.990" end="00:07:02.930" tts:direction="ltr">Let's look back at the big picture and
<br />taking all of this data into account.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:02.930" end="00:07:07.810" tts:direction="ltr">It may be time to consider altering our
<br />people strategy.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:07.810" end="00:07:13.330" tts:direction="ltr">Let's shift energy towards promotions and
<br />transfers into the organization.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:13.330" end="00:07:19.330" tts:direction="ltr">When we do that, I believe we can
<br />substantially reduce these red bars.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:19.330" end="00:07:23.430" tts:direction="ltr">Now, to summarize this on a slide.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:23.430" end="00:07:25.690" tts:direction="ltr">I have a recommendation to</p>
        <p begin="00:07:25.690" end="00:07:29.490" tts:direction="ltr">increase efforts to hire from within the
<br />organization.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:29.490" end="00:07:33.110" tts:direction="ltr">This would include fast tracking internal
<br />transfers</p>
        <p begin="00:07:33.110" end="00:07:35.270" tts:direction="ltr">into sales manager positions,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:35.270" end="00:07:39.650" tts:direction="ltr">adding a second annual promotion cycle in
<br />April,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:39.650" end="00:07:42.530" tts:direction="ltr">hopefully alleviating the stress from</p>
        <p begin="00:07:42.530" end="00:07:47.990" tts:direction="ltr">leadership and giving those who are
<br />performing well another chance earlier.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:47.990" end="00:07:53.090" tts:direction="ltr">We can also introduce an approval process
<br />for off cycle promotions.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:53.090" end="00:07:55.910" tts:direction="ltr">Now, I'm sure you also have a few ideas,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:55.910" end="00:07:58.110" tts:direction="ltr">so I'm looking forward to discussing those
<br />with</p>
        <p begin="00:07:58.110" end="00:08:01.430" tts:direction="ltr">you and to determine our approach.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:02.030" end="00:08:07.870" tts:direction="ltr">I just provided with you a stellar story
<br />success.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:07.870" end="00:08:09.950" tts:direction="ltr">As you could see,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:09.950" end="00:08:15.470" tts:direction="ltr">there was a clear beginning middle end
<br />that included an action.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:15.470" end="00:08:21.610" tts:direction="ltr">I would also create some executive slide
<br />or executive summary.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:21.610" end="00:08:23.735" tts:direction="ltr">You'll do this for your own project.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:23.735" end="00:08:26.880" tts:direction="ltr">While I would not give it to them at the
<br />beginning,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:26.880" end="00:08:29.740" tts:direction="ltr">I could leave this with them as a takeaway</p>
        <p begin="00:08:29.740" end="00:08:33.620" tts:direction="ltr">or I could provide it to those who are
<br />unable to attend the meeting.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:33.620" end="00:08:40.440" tts:direction="ltr">You can see here I've got this waterfall
<br />chart with those actions to consider.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:40.720" end="00:08:45.040" tts:direction="ltr">I hope that this has been helpful for you
<br />to</p>
        <p begin="00:08:45.040" end="00:08:49.840" tts:direction="ltr">understand how to tell an explanatory
<br />story.</p>
    </div>
  </body>
</tt>
